NS.301 | Navigation | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=NS.301 Navigation | prereq:ns.202 instructors:D. Lueck term:U (Spring) description:Comprehensive study of the theory, principles, and procedures of piloting and maritime navigation, including mathematics of navigation, practical work involving navigational instruments, sight reduction by pro forma and computerized methods, charts, publications, and voyage planning. CORTRAMID cruise recommended.  2-2-4 units
NS.302 | Navigation and Naval Operations | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=NS.302 Navigation and Naval Operations | prereq:recommended first class cruise and ns.301 instructors:D. Lueck term:U (Fall) description:Comprehensive study of tactical and strategic considerations to the employment of naval forces, including communications, tactical formations and dispositions, relative motion, maneuvering board, and nautical rules of the road.  3-0-3 units
NS.310 | Evolution of Warfare | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=NS.310 Evolution of Warfare | prereq:none instructors:M. Hritz term:U (Spring) description:Traces development of warfare from dawn of recorded history to present, focusing on the impact of major military theorists, strategists, tacticians, and technological developments. Seeks to understand the relationships between military training, weaponry, strategies and tactics, and the societies and cultures that produce and then are defended by those military structures. By examining the association between a society and its military, students acquire basic sense of strategy, develop an understanding of military alternatives, and see the impact of historical precedents on military thoughts and actions.  2-0-4 units
